2026-05-10 | Maximum Number of Jumps to Reach End

	Question
Return maximum jumps to reach n-1.
	Key Insight
Since jumps only move forward:
		graph is a DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph)
So:
		use DP for longest path.
	Approach
1.	Define:
		dp[i] =
			max jumps needed to reach index i  
2.	Initialize:
		dp[0] = 0  
		all others = -1  
3.	For every pair (j → i):
		if valid jump:
			dp[i] = max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1)
4.	Final answer:
		dp[n-1]
	Time Complexity
	O(n²)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumJumps(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<int> dp(n, -1);
        dp[0] = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j < i; j++){
                if(dp[j] != -1 &&
                   abs(nums[i] - nums[j]) <= target){
                    dp[i] = max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[n-1];
    }
};
	Key Insight
This is essentially:
		longest valid path in forward graph  
Because movement is only forward:
		no cycles exist  
So dynamic programming works naturally.
